{
  "brand": "NEC",
  "device": "PROJECTOR",
  "variant": "NEC NP / PA / PX / P / V series (Binary protocol)",
  "controlType": "RS232",
  "notes": [
    "Source: 'Projector Control Command Reference Manual' (NEC Display Solutions, BDT140013 rev 7.1, 2014-2020).",
    "Wire: D-Sub 9-pin cross-over. 9600 8N1 (also supports 38400/19200/115200), full duplex.",
    "Packet format: <CMD> <CMD2> <ID1> <ID2> <LEN> [<DATA>...] <CKS>. CKS = (sum of all preceding bytes) mod 256. ID1=ID2=00 for broadcast / non-daisy-chain.",
    "POWER ON / OFF / mute commands use fixed 6-byte packets with no ID bytes (legacy format).",
    "Source selection uses Remote Key Code (cmd 050): COMPUTER1=4B, COMPUTER2=4C, VIDEO1=4F, S-VIDEO1=51, or SOURCE (toggle)=D7. HDMI/DVI/DisplayPort require Input SW Change (cmd 018) with model-specific input IDs from the manual's appendix — omitted here to avoid sending incorrect codes.",
    "Status request responses are binary frames starting 20H/21H/22H/23H + cmd echo + ID + DATA + CKS. For POWER STATUS REQUEST (00 85 00 00 01 01 87) the reply byte DATA01: 00H=standby, 04H=power on, 05H=cooling, 06H=standby error. For INFORMATION REQUEST (03 8A 00 00 00 8D) DATA83-86 = lamp seconds (little-endian), DATA87-90 = filter seconds. For BASIC INFORMATION REQUEST (00 BF 00 00 01 02 C2) DATA02: 00H=Idle, 04H=Power On, 05H=Cooling, 06H=Idle(Error)."
  ],
